<paper id="1502416796"><title>Zero knowledge proofs of knowledge in two rounds</title><year>1989</year><authors><author org="The Weizmann Institute of Science" id="672946669">Uriel Feige</author><author org="The Weizmann Institute of Science" id="2201755339">Adi Shamir</author></authors><n_citation>233</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1496572999</reference><reference>1536808194</reference><reference>1600605837</reference><reference>1667049494</reference><reference>1970606468</reference><reference>1979215153</reference><reference>2012045293</reference><reference>2027528470</reference><reference>2036265926</reference><reference>2045664183</reference><reference>2133203144</reference><reference>2137883105</reference><reference>2151433956</reference><reference>2151715405</reference><reference>2152005134</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/0-387-34805-0_46</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.42425">Authentication</keyword><keyword weight="0.46004">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.43747">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.53591">Commitment scheme</keyword><keyword weight="0.44856">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43753">Digital signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.40764">Electronic funds transfer</keyword><keyword weight="0.50576">Zero-knowledge proof</keyword><keyword weight="0.40312">Electronic signature</keyword><keyword weight="0.46875">Discrete logarithm</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, New York, NY</publisher><abstract>We construct constant round ZKIPs for any NP language, under the sole assumption that oneway functions exist. Under the stronger Certified Discrete Log assumption, our construction yields perfect zero knowledge protocols. Our protocols rely on two novel ideas: One for constructing commitment schemes, the other for constructing subprotocols which are not known to be zero knowledge, yet can be proven not to reveal useful information.</abstract></paper>